<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pile it up out in the desert, build a fence around it, and put signs on the fence: &quot;DANGER: Nuclear Waste. If you cross this fence, you will DIE&quot;. Admittedly, there will be people willing to cross the fence. Just think of it as evolution in action.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
    The same article also suggested turning it into money. &quot;The concept of money burning a hole in your pocket would take on an entirely new meaning....the economy would speed up. There would be other advantages as well. Foreign aid could be delivered by ICBM, for instance.&quot;<br>
    All pretty silly.  The fact is that radioactivity and half-life vary enormously within the material, but the media cannot mention it without generalizing that it is all &quot;deadly&quot;. <br>
<br>
 I don't believe that &quot;burying&quot; nuclear waste is such a good idea. The public is led to think that this is necessary to block &quot;deadly&quot; radiation, which is absurd. I suspect that the real reason for deep underground storage is to get it out of the weather, and out of sight. The former can be done above ground, and the latter is a weasel trick based on allaying misconceptions rather than correcting them. Putting it hundreds of meters under solid rock will block &quot;deadly&quot; radiation, so will a few meters of dirt, and the deep storage would make the material much harder to get to if things really come unravelled. And they might. Over a period of thousands of years, all kinds of things can happen underground that will not happen on the surface. No matter what the DOE says, it is just not possible to declare that a particular formation will be so stable for the next 250,000 years that even a minor tunnel collapse can be ruled out. Stresses migrate on a very small scale, even in highly stable formations. We can rule out a major earthquake or a volcanic eruption at Yucca Mountain for millions of years. A tunnel collapse or even a minor change in level and alignment is simply below the threshold of prediction, however. Either of these things could completely disrupt the facility. <br>
      Unpredictable surface events can affect this. Will a new irrigation project in 100,000CE change the water table? Will altered erosion patterns cause an unpredictable re-alignment of stresses? What will the weather be like in 100,000 years?<br>
      Anti-nuclear activists have pointed all this out; rightly, for once; but DOE has cleverly shifted the burden of proof to them. This is a dangerous fallacy, nobody has to prove that the proposed facility is unsafe, DOE has to prove that it is safe for the proposed duration. That is a daunting task when we are looking into the very remote future.   <br>
  <br>
     For instance, will some future conspiracy cult or shamanistic religion try to dig it up? According to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Omni</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, DOE looked into some very exotic and paranoid ways of communicating the danger to future societies that may have no memory of our present era. I think this is vanishingly unlikely, but it is typical of DOE's fantasy land approach to the problem. They have had linguists devise warning pictograms that would be meaningful to all. Geologists have analyzed the durability of stone inscriptions (they favored incising the warnings into rounded granite blocks). Wonderful. What better way to encourage future druids to dig the stuff up than to mark it as some kind of deadly magic? They would fight each other for the privilege. There would be tribal wars over &quot;sacred digging rights&quot;. <br>
     <br>
Worst case scenarios, like asteroid collisions and large scale attack, mitigate against a single storage facility in any case. The fact is, the DOE notion of making this stuff absolutely safe even if civilization collapses is just unrealistic. It can be placed where little maintenance is required, but some maintenance and monitoring will always be necessary as long as the stuff is here with us on Earth.<br>
    <br>
The best immediate solution is to dilute the material as much as practicable, below the danger level when possible, turn it into glass blocks too heavy to be easily moved, and stash this stuff where someone can keep an eye on it. <br>
